Slideshow: Amazing Rescues	
					Rescue of Chilean Miners Begins
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/chile-miners1.jpg
                    
					On August 5, 2010, Chile's San Jose gold and copper mine collapsed, trapping 33 miners thousands of feet below the surface. After 69 days underground, the world watched as their dramatic rescue began on October 12. (Photo Credit: AFP/Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					US Airways Flight 1549 in the Hudson
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/us-airways-15491.jpg
                    
					About a minute after taking off from New York's La Guardia Airport on January 15, 2009, US Airways Flight 1549 collided with a flock of geese. Both engines lost power, forcing Captain Chesley Burnett Sullenberger III to make an emergency landing on the Hudson River. All 150 passengers were rescued. (Photo Credit: Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Rescue of Maersk Alabama Captain from Pirates
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/somali-pirates1.jpg
                    
					On April 8, 2009, a small band of Somali pirates hijacked the American cargo ship Maersk Alabama and took its captain, Richard Phillips, hostage. After a standoff that lasted several days, Navy SEAL sharpshooters took out his captors with just three shots. (Photo Credit: Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					The Rescue of Baby Jessica
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/baby-jessica1.jpg
                    
					On October 14, 1987, an 18-month-old girl named Jessica McClure fell into an abandoned well. Her story captivated the public, and reporters descended on Midland, Texas, to cover the massive effort to rescue her. After more than two days, she was brought to the surface alive by a team of rescuers. (Photo Credit: Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Site of the Andes Crash Survivors' Camp
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/andes-crash1.jpg
                    
					On October 13, 1972, a chartered flight carrying a Uruguayan rugby team and a group of their friends and family members slammed into a peak in the Andes mountains. After 72 days on a desolate mountaintop during which the survivors resorted to cannibalism, 16 of the 45 passengers were found alive.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					The Apollo 13 Crew and President Nixon
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/apollo-131.jpg
                    
					When an explosion rocked the Apollo 13 spaceship on April 13, 1970, the third lunar landing mission quickly became a fight for survival for the three men on board and an intense rescue operation for mission control in Houston. The astronauts survived by returning in the spacecraft's lunar module. (Photo Credit: NASA)
